<h2>
    <a href="/blog/searching-for-pi-mnemonic-strings-in-a-text/">Searching for pi-mnemonic strings in a text</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    
    on 19 Dec 2019
</h6>





<a href="/blog/searching-for-pi-mnemonic-strings-in-a-text/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/pi-mnemonic/.thumbnails/word_length_frequencies.png/word_length_frequencies-90x90.png">
</a>





<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piphilology">Piphilology</a> comprises the creation and use of mnemonic techniques to remember a span of digits of the mathematical constant $\pi$. One famous technique, attributed to the physicist <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Jeans">James Jeans</a> uses the number of letters in each word of the sentence:</p>




